\[
\begin{cases}
A_{510}= \varepsilon_{\text{Co},510}\,c_{\text{Co}}+\varepsilon_{\text{Ni},510}\,c_{\text{Ni}}\\[2pt]
A_{656}= \varepsilon_{\text{Co},656}\,c_{\text{Co}}+\varepsilon_{\text{Ni},656}\,c_{\text{Ni}}
\end{cases}
\]

with \(l=1.00\;\text{cm}\).

\[
\begin{aligned}
36400\,c_{\text{Co}}+5520\,c_{\text{Ni}} &=0.446 \qquad (1)\\
1240\,c_{\text{Co}}+17500\,c_{\text{Ni}} &=0.326 \qquad (2)
\end{aligned}
\]

Solving (1)–(2) gives the concentration of Ni in the **final** measurement solution:

\[
c_{\text{Ni}}^{\text{(final)}} = 1.80\times10^{-5}\;\text{mol L}^{-1}
\]

The final solution was prepared by taking \(25.0\;\text{mL}\) of the original 50‑mL dilution and diluting it back to \(50.0\;\text{mL}\); therefore the concentration in the original 50‑mL dilution is twice as large:

\[
c_{\text{Ni}}^{\text{(initial)}} = 2\,c_{\text{Ni}}^{\text{(final)}} = 3.59\times10^{-5}\;\text{mol L}^{-1}
\]

Moles of Ni present in the 50‑mL solution that originally contained the sample:

\[
n_{\text{Ni}} = c_{\text{Ni}}^{\text{(initial)}}\times 0.050\;\text{L}
               = 3.59\times10^{-5}\times 0.050
               = 1.80\times10^{-6}\;\text{mol}
\]

Mass of Ni (using \(M_{\text{Ni}} = 58.69\;\text{g mol}^{-1}\)):

\[
m_{\text{Ni}} = n_{\text{Ni}}M_{\text{Ni}}
               = 1.80\times10^{-6}\times 58.69
               = 1.05\times10^{-4}\;\text{g}
               = 0.105\;\text{mg}
\]

The original solid sample weighed \(0.425\;\text{g}=0.000425\;\text{kg}\).  
Thus the nickel concentration in the sample (ppm = mg kg\(^{-1}\)) is

\[
\text{Ni (ppm)} = \frac{0.105\;\text{mg}}{0.000425\;\text{kg}}
                = 2.48\times10^{2}\;\text{ppm}
\]

\[
\boxed{2.48\times10^{2}}\;\text{Ni(ppm)}
\]

The degree of polymerisation (average number of monomer units per chain) is obtained from  

\[
\text{DP}= \frac{M_{\text{average}}}{M_{\text{repeat unit}}}
\]

For poly(lactic acid) the repeat‑unit mass is  

\[
M_{\text{repeat unit}} = 3(12.01) + 4(1.008) + 2(16.00)= 72.06\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

Given \(M_{\text{average}} = 595\;\text{g mol}^{-1}\),

\[
\text{DP}= \frac{595\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}{72.06\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}
          = 8.26\;\text{(dimensionless)}
\]

\[
\boxed{8.3}
\] (average number of monomer units per polymer chain).

The amount of \(\ce{KOH}\) used corresponds to the number of carboxyl end‑groups, i.e. to the number of polymer chains.

\[
\begin{aligned}
V_{\ce{KOH}} &= 6.81\ \text{cm}^{3}=6.81\times10^{-3}\ \text{L}\\[4pt]
c_{\ce{KOH}} &= 0.0400\ \text{mol L}^{-1}\\[4pt]
n_{\ce{KOH}} &= c_{\ce{KOH}}\,V_{\ce{KOH}}
            = 0.0400\ \frac{\text{mol}}{\text{L}}\times 6.81\times10^{-3}\ \text{L}\\
            &= 2.724\times10^{-4}\ \text{mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus the number of polymer molecules (chains) in the sample is  

\[
n_{\text{PLA}} = n_{\ce{KOH}} = 2.724\times10^{-4}\ \text{mol}
\]

The average molar mass \(M_{\text{avg}}\) is the mass of the sample divided by the number of moles of chains:

\[
\begin{aligned}
M_{\text{avg}} &= \frac{m_{\text{PLA}}}{n_{\text{PLA}}}
               = \frac{0.1619\ \text{g}}{2.724\times10^{-4}\ \text{mol}}\\[4pt]
               &= 5.95\times10^{2}\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{5.95\times10^{2}\ \text{g mol}^{-1}}
\]

The Cr in \([\mathrm{Cr}(\mathrm{NH}_{3})_{6}]^{3+}\) is in the +3 oxidation state, giving a \(d^{3}\) configuration.  
Thus the number of unpaired electrons \(n = 3\).

The spin‑only magnetic moment is  

\[
\mu_{\text{so}} = \sqrt{n(n+2)}\;\text{BM}
               = \sqrt{3(3+2)}\;\text{BM}
               = \sqrt{15}\;\text{BM}
               \approx 3.87\;\text{BM}.
\]

\[
\boxed{3.87}\ \text{BM}
\]

For a linear diatomic molecule the rotational partition function in the high‑temperature limit is  

\[
q_{\text{rot}}=\frac{k_{\mathrm B}T}{\sigma h c B}
          =\frac{T}{\sigma \,\theta_{\text{rot}}}\;,
\]

where  

* \(\sigma\) – symmetry number (for \(\ce{O2}\), \(\sigma = 2\)),  
* \(B\) – rotational constant (in cm\(^{-1}\)),  
* \(\theta_{\text{rot}} = \dfrac{h c B}{k_{\mathrm B}}\) – characteristic rotational temperature.

---

### 1. Moment of inertia  

The reduced mass of \(\ce{O2}\) is  

\[
\mu = \frac{m_{\mathrm O}}{2}= \frac{16\;\text{amu}}{2}
     = 8\;\text{amu}
     = 8 \times 1.66054\times10^{-27}\,\text{kg}
     = 1.3284\times10^{-26}\,\text{kg}.
\]

With the bond length \(r = 120.75\;\text{pm}=1.2075\times10^{-10}\,\text{m}\),

\[
I = \mu r^{2}
  = (1.3284\times10^{-26})(1.2075\times10^{-10})^{2}
  = 1.94\times10^{-46}\,\text{kg·m}^{2}.
\]

---

### 2. Rotational constant \(B\)

\[
B = \frac{h}{8\pi^{2}cI}
   = \frac{6.62607\times10^{-34}\,\text{J·s}}
          {8\pi^{2}(2.99792\times10^{10}\,\text{cm·s}^{-1})(1.94\times10^{-46}\,\text{kg·m}^{2})}
   \approx 1.44\;\text{cm}^{-1}.
\]

---

### 3. Characteristic rotational temperature  

\[
\theta_{\text{rot}} = \frac{h c B}{k_{\mathrm B}}
   = \frac{(6.62607\times10^{-34})(2.99792\times10^{10})(1.44)}
          {1.38065\times10^{-23}}
   \approx 2.08\;\text{K}.
\]

---

### 4. Rotational partition function at \(T = 300\;\text{K}\)

\[
q_{\text{rot}} = \frac{T}{\sigma \,\theta_{\text{rot}}}
                = \frac{300\;\text{K}}{2 \times 2.08\;\text{K}}
                \approx 7.22\times10^{1}
                \approx 72.
\]

\[
\boxed{72}
\]  

(The partition function is dimensionless.)
